<article class="article-body">

<p>"What does a Chief of Staff actually <em>do</em> all day?" is a fair question — the role is invisible when it's done well. Here's a representative week, so you can see the work behind the title.</p>

<h2>Monday — set the week</h2>
<p>Run the leadership meeting from an agenda built off last week's decision log and open commitments. Capture every decision with an owner and a date. By Monday lunch, the whole company knows what matters this week and who's accountable.</p>

<h2>Tuesday — follow-through</h2>
<p>The unglamorous core of the job: chasing the commitments made Monday before they quietly die. This is where companies leak momentum, and where a Chief of Staff earns their keep.</p>

<h2>Wednesday — the strategic initiative</h2>
<p>Deep work on the one or two cross-functional projects the CoS owns end-to-end this quarter — a market entry, a systems migration, a partnership. Stakeholder calls, status discipline, blockers escalated with options attached.</p>

<h2>Thursday — board &amp; investor operations</h2>
<p>Draft the investor update from real metrics, assemble the board pack days ahead (never the night before), triage intro requests. The rhythm that replaces quarterly panic.</p>

<h2>Friday — the CEO brief</h2>
<p>One document: what moved, what's blocked, what needs the founder's decision — each with a recommendation attached. Plus the OKR pulse-check that keeps quarterly goals alive past week three. The founder reads one page instead of chasing ten threads.</p>

<h2>The thread running through all of it</h2>
<p>A Chief of Staff converts a founder's scattered priorities into a tracked, accountable operating system. The output isn't activity — it's strategic projects that actually ship and a leadership team that moves without the founder in the middle of everything.</p>

<p>This is the fractional version of the role for most companies — see <a href="/blog/what-does-fractional-chief-of-staff-do/">what a fractional Chief of Staff does</a> and the <a href="/fractional-chief-of-staff/">fractional CoS page</a>. Not sure it's the role you need? Compare it in <a href="/blog/chief-of-staff-vs-executive-assistant/">Chief of Staff vs Executive Assistant</a>, or <a href="/booking/">book a free call</a>.</p>

